 for homes.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
And it makes sense. Henry Ford figured out that assembly lines decrease cos=
ts over a century ago, and we=E2=80=99ve been riding his lessons to materia=
l abundance ever since. You and I wouldn=E2=80=99t be able to afford cars i=
f Tesla had to send a team to our driveways to assemble the parts on-site. =
There would be no Moore=E2=80=99s Law if each chip had to be assembled one-=
at-a-time at the location of the computer it was going to serve.=C2=A0
No, centralized manufacturing is key. The benefits of manufacturing are man=
ifold: efficiency, speed, cost, consistency, safety, precision, scalability=
, and even innovation. Manufacturing something lets you bring it down the l=
earning curve: as you make more of the thing, you make it more cheaply.
If you want to apply the magic of the assembly line to homebuilding, there =
are broadly two approaches you can take:=C2=A0
Prefabricated Homes: Homes are assembled in sections or modules in a centra=
lized factory, and then shipped onsite, where they=E2=80=99re assembled on =
a permanent foundation.
Manufactured Homes: Homes are built entirely in a factory, transported onsi=
te on a steel chassis (which often stays in place), and then plopped onsite=
=2E=C2=A0
Manufactured homes are their own distinct category =E2=80=93 they are cooki=
e-cutter, often cheap, and they depreciate like cars do. These are not typi=
cal homes you=E2=80=99re thinking of when you think about a home =E2=80=93 =
they=E2=80=99re built differently, face different regulations, and generall=
y have a lower perceived value. There are some large manufactured homes com=
panies, like Clayton Homes, which Berkshire Hathaway acquired for $1.7 bill=
ion in 2003, but they serve a specific niche, the low-end of the market.=C2=
=A0=C2=A0
Prefab homes are more similar to traditional site-built homes, with more cu=
stomization available. You might see a prefab home and have no idea that it=
=E2=80=99s a prefab home.=C2=A0That=E2=80=99s what we=E2=80=99re after here=
 =E2=80=94 homes that look like homes, built better.
Prefab homes have been housing innovators=E2=80=99 White Whale since as ear=
ly as the 1920s, when Buckminster Fuller created the Dymaxion House. Even F=
ord himself toyed with the idea.
A century later, it=E2=80=99s still an unsolved problem. Looking at Bucky=
=E2=80=99s Dymaxion =E2=80=93 just looking at it =E2=80=93 provides one clu=
e as to why. Would you want to live in that?=C2=A0
Henry Ford himself could have told you the Dymaxion House would never work.=
=C2=A0
In his autobiography, My Life and Work [ https://substack.com/redirect/91b4=
40e2-42bd-45cb-a952-be9c7a5f0eff?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZj=
mlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], he writes: =E2=80=9CWhere most manufacturers fi=
nd themselves quicker to make a change in the product than in the method of=
 manufacturing =E2=80=93 we follow exactly the opposite course. Our big cha=
nges have been in the methods of manufacturing.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Buckminster Fuller, and scores of intrepid entrepreneurs since, have attemp=
ted to change the home to make it more manufacturable, instead of changing =
the method of manufacturing to match the task of building a home.=C2=A0
A decade after Bucky, no less an architectural eminence than Frank Lloyd Wr=
ight tried to design prefabricated, user-assembled homes. He called them Us=
onian Automatic Homes [ https://substack.com/redirect/7821369f-9b4f-484c-be=
46-813a39d0dcd1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ], and they were made of inexpensive concrete blocks that could be =
assembled in a variety of configurations. As this lovely website [ https://=
substack.com/redirect/7821369f-9b4f-484c-be46-813a39d0dcd1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAw=
Z3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] explains, =E2=80=9CWri=
ght hoped that home buyers could save money by building their own Usonian A=
utomatic houses. But assembling the modular parts proved complicated, and m=
ost hired contractors to build their Usonian houses.=E2=80=9D
None of these concepts reached scale, and none operate today.=C2=A0
So this is one lesson from the history of prefab housing: don=E2=80=99t cha=
nge the house, change how you build it.=C2=A0
You can take standardization too far though. Projects like Levittown =E2=80=
=93 entirely pre-planned developments of nearly identical homes manufacture=
d on an assembly line and assembled in as little as one day =E2=80=93 sprun=
g up in the wake of WWII, as soldiers came home, started families, and, bac=
kstopped by the Veterans Administration and Federal Housing Administration,=
 bought homes. When you think of a Pleasantville, the Technicolor 1950s nei=
ghborhood with perfectly identical perfect homes, you=E2=80=99re thinking o=
f something like Levittown.=C2=A0
Levittown succeeded in building and installing a lot of affordable houses q=
uickly. It failed in other important ways, like being racist [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/e74bcf82-9d91-4d7b-8a8a-6de2895a82b2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and in the fact that the l=
ack of diversity in the homes themselves fell out of favor as people shunne=
d homogeneity in the 1960s and 1970s. Plus, there were concerns about how t=
he quality of the homes themselves, and their sameness, would impact home v=
alues over time. We don=E2=80=99t really build Levittowns anymore.=C2=A0
So this is another lesson: customization is key.=C2=A0
This is true because people prefer not to sacrifice their personal preferen=
ces for affordability, and more practically, because each location is diffe=
rent. Local regulations and codes are different. Local tastes are different=
=2E Each individual site takes different shapes and grades.=C2=A0
So in the late 1990s and early 2000s, the =E2=80=9CPrefab 1.0=E2=80=9D move=
ment reimagined the possibilities of prefabrication based on lessons from e=
arlier attempts. Their goal was to deliver modern, stylish homes more effic=
iently and affordably, and they focused on aesthetics, sustainability, and =
customization to separate themselves from earlier prefab homes in buyers=E2=
=80=99 minds.=C2=A0
The question: could you give people homes they actually wanted to live in f=
aster and cheaper by building components in factories?=C2=A0
The answer: kind of. Halfway. Almost. So, in short, no.=C2=A0
As Tom Chi, the Google X co-founder whose At One Ventures led Cuby=E2=80=99=
s Series A, explained to me, =E2=80=9CThe Prefab 1.0 movement realized a lo=
t of wins. If you build a lot inside a covered facility, you don=E2=80=99t =
have construction delays from weather and people can be at a station in saf=
e condition with their tools around them. You get a higher worker utilizati=
on per day, and a higher quality build at a lower cost.=E2=80=9D=20
That=E2=80=99s the good half.=C2=A0
The problem, Tom said, is that they, =E2=80=9CAchieved half the dream. They=
 ended up getting a lot of elements pre-built. But you still needed to move=
 the entire house=E2=80=99s worth of weight somewhere.=E2=80=9D
What happened, in very broad strokes, is that Prefab 1.0 took a home that w=
ould have cost $500k site-built, actually built it for $350k in a centraliz=
ed factory, but then needed to pay a ton of money to move the house in huge=
 sections to the site and hired skilled labor to assemble it. Add in the fa=
ct that most players served just one piece in the value chain, and had some=
one else installing their components, which meant mistakes, rework, and lon=
g feedback loops, and all in, you ended up with something that cost maybe $=
650k, 30% more than site-built:=C2=A0
It was still manual labor, but putting it in a line setting produced real a=
dvantages on the build side. But the landed cost was higher, and a bit unce=
rtain, because you were moving in huge housing sections, using double-wides=
 and long beds, you=E2=80=99d need to cut down trees just to turn corners, =
some prefabs even needed heavy-lift helicopters to drop them in. That=E2=80=
=99s why it ballooned in cost.=C2=A0
This is a third lesson: logistics costs can kill prefab economics.
Brian Potter [ https://substack.com/redirect/6862ef3a-119e-4d8c-8a43-4c187f=
6da7b7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=
, the author of the best construction blog on the internet, Construction Ph=
ysics [ https://substack.com/redirect/b0e4c1ef-f63b-41a1-83dd-8d48c2199813?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], wrote=
 an excellent piece on this titled Logistics, Production Volume, and Indust=
rialized Building [ https://substack.com/redirect/206c0619-dabd-415e-a266-3=
35e96c6dcbb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ]. He makes the case that whether factories should be centralized or de=
centralized comes down to product value density: the ratio of a product=E2=
=80=99s cost to its weight or volume. =E2=80=9CThe lower the density,=E2=80=
=9D he explains, =E2=80=9Cthe greater the relative fraction logistics costs=
 (transportation, storage, etc.) are of overall cost.=E2=80=9D
iPhones have high product value density, so they can be made in China and s=
hipped around the world. Homes have low product density, so they need to be=
 made near demand.=C2=A0
Because it costs what it costs to transport a shipping container over the s=
ame distance, as long as you=E2=80=99re within weight limits, shipping a 40=
-foot container full of tightly-packed 2x4s is more cost-effective than shi=
pping a container with fully constructed wall panels or even rooms, which c=
ontain a lot of empty volume.=C2=A0
This is one of the reasons that so much of construction is just sending fin=
ished inputs (windows, doors, cabinetry, fixtures, flooring, and appliances=
) and non-finished inputs (like lumber, concrete, drywall, insulation, and =
roofing materials) to the site for local crews to take care of.=C2=A0 Even =
still, the current process requires skilled labor to do messy, non-structur=
ed work to them even before install, resulting in mistakes, lots of rework,=
 and waste. Building an average 2,000 square foot home generates four tons =
of waste [ https://substack.com/redirect/91003d89-3c70-4f60-8076-d90040a5c0=
80?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]!
Pre-fab 1.0 was stuck somewhere in between: higher logistics costs, a littl=
e less waste, a lot of on-site work and assembly. Paying so much on logisti=
cs and then paying skilled people to handle so much on-site makes the econo=
mics hard to pencil.
More than anything else, this is what killed Prefab 1.0.=C2=A0
Prefab 1.0 was almost a product in search of a problem. It was driven by ne=
w technology =E2=80=93 Computer-Aided Design (CAD), Building Information Mo=
deling (BIM), and Computer Numerical Control (CNC) Machines =E2=80=93 and t=
he belief that maybe, now, with these new technological tools, we might fin=
ally be able to realize the dream of doing to homes what Ford did to cars.=
=C2=A0
Cars, however, are different than homes. For one important thing, they are =
mobile: once assembled, you can drive them off the line. More efficiently, =
you can put a bunch of them on the back of one truck and carry them to the =
lot that will sell them to the customers who will drive them home. You don=
=E2=80=99t need to cut down trees or hire helicopters to get cars from the =
place they=E2=80=99re made to the place they=E2=80=99ll be used, nor do you=
 have to do final assembly in the driveway, calling in teams of skilled pro=
fessionals to snap their pieces into place, hook them up to plumbing, or co=
nnect their wires.=C2=A0
So here=E2=80=99s a fourth lesson: centralized gigafactories don=E2=80=99t =
work for home construction.
Expensive, centralized factories have a number of disadvantages: they requi=
re more capital and time to launch, before the process is perfected, feedba=
ck from the site takes longer, they can=E2=80=99t produce with specific loc=
al codes in mind, and you need to keep running the factory even when demand=
 slows due to high fixed costs.=C2=A0
Above all else, if you build something for less in the factory, and pay mor=
e than you=E2=80=99ve saved to transport and assemble it, you increase cost=
s. And increased costs don=E2=80=99t work.=C2=A0
If there=E2=80=99s one thing developers will not countenance, it=E2=80=99s =
adding cost. They like making money, and more contractually, they=E2=80=99r=
e obligated to pay back the debt they take on to get each project going. Th=
e formula that drives them is:=C2=A0
Return on Investment =3D (Sale Price - Costs) / Costs=C2=A0
There are others, of course. They care about IRR and ROC and Profit Margin =
and Absorption Rate and Debt Service Coverage Ratio and Construction Cost p=
er Square Foot and Sales Price per Square Foot and Inventory Turnover, not =
a single one of which improves with higher costs.=C2=A0
So this is a fifth, and maybe most important, lesson: don=E2=80=99t increas=
e costs.
Which brings us to Katerra.=C2=A0
Katerra is worth studying on its own because it was the most well-funded, a=
mbitious, and modern attempt to build a Vertical Integrator in housing cons=
truction. It fit the Vertical Integrator definition almost to a T. But that=
 almost was the difference between a $100 billion outcome and $2 billion of=
 (mostly) SoftBank=E2=80=99s money down the drain.=C2=A0
What Went Wrong at Katerra=C2=A0
I want to start this section, the last in our foraging of memory lane, by p=
ointing out that this is not a knock on Katerra. The company was incredibly=
 ambitious and full of people with more brains, talent, and experience than=
 I have.=C2=A0This is just really hard.
In his retrospective on the company, Another Day in Katerradise [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/38f785f4-4ac0-4d71-b350-27f594ea4906?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Potter, a former Kater=
ra employee himself, writes: =E2=80=9CAt the time, I thought this was the e=
xact right strategy needed to change the construction industry - it couldn=
=E2=80=99t be done piecemeal, it needed to be done all at once, simultaneou=
sly attacking every stage in the process.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
If I knew enough then, I=E2=80=99m sure I would have thought the same thing=
=2E Hindsight is 20/20. But that=E2=80=99s=
 the point: each failed attempt bri=
ngs us a step closer to the right one, if we learn the lessons.=C2=A0
Katerra=E2=80=99s founding insight seemed to be: previous attempts at fixin=
g housing construction weren=E2=80=99t vertically integrated enough. Here=
=E2=80=99s Potter:
Instead of laboriously constructing buildings one at a time, by hand, build=
ings would be built the way everything else was built - prefabricated in a =
factory, designed specifically to be manufactured as efficiently as possibl=
e. Instead of designing buildings from scratch every single time, Katerra w=
ould have building products: standard, off the shelf buildings that could b=
e customized for a client=E2=80=99s needs, the same way mass produced cars =
offer a wide variety of trim options.
This was the Katerra playbook when I joined the company. They would design =
a series of building products that could be mass-produced in their own fact=
ories, leveraging economies of scale and advanced manufacturing to build mo=
re efficiently than conventional construction. These products would be full=
 of Katerra-supplied materials - everything from lightbulbs, to countertops=
, to bathroom fixtures, to appliances would all be Katerra brand. They woul=
d acquire general contractors in different markets to give them a nationwid=
e construction footprint, and hire the various trades to self-perform all t=
he construction work.
Katerra applied some of the lessons =E2=80=93 don=E2=80=99t change the home=
, but don=E2=80=99t make them all the same =E2=80=93 and seems to have igno=
red others =E2=80=93 logistics can kill prefab economics, gigafactories don=
=E2=80=99t work, and ultimately, your fancy process cannot increase costs.=
=C2=A0
But maybe viewing Katerra as a housing construction company primarily is th=
e wrong way to look at it. They may have primarily been a building material=
s company that used their prefabricated houses as a distribution channel an=
d first and best customer.=20
As Potter explains, =E2=80=9CThey could (theoretically) afford to sell buil=
dings for at or near cost, and simply use them as a vehicle to sell as many=
 building materials as possible (similar to how manufactured home builders =
often make a large fraction of their profits from financing the homes).=E2=
=80=9D
Because Katerra thought it had found a magical money glitch, and because it=
 was oriented around selling materials that it had vertically integrated, i=
t decided to offer a number of different products through which to sell mat=
erials: =E2=80=9CBut the economics of factory production still hold - makin=
g the numbers work requires maximizing your factory=E2=80=99s production vo=
lume. Katerra planned to do this with a series of standard, off-the-shelf b=
uildings that it could prefabricate and sell all over the country.=E2=80=9D=
 Potter compiled a list of all of the different products that Katerra offer=
ed:=C2=A0
Katerra scaled and vertically integrated too much before it had a product t=
hat customers actually wanted to buy. They hadn=E2=80=99t figured out how t=
o make prefab competitive with stick-built construction, which meant that t=
here wasn=E2=80=99t enough demand for the =E2=80=9Cdistribution=E2=80=9D pr=
oducts to sell the actual products, the materials. It also meant that the c=
ompany, though =E2=80=9Cpre-Product Market Fit,=E2=80=9D was too large and =
unwieldy to iterate quickly to the right products and economics. =E2=80=9CI=
deally, early stage product development involves rapid iteration and protot=
yping, to figure out what needs to be built as quickly as possible,=E2=80=
=9D Potter writes. =E2=80=9CBut the pace of product development at Katerra =
always felt sluggish.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Here is one big lesson from Katerra: don=E2=80=99t vertically integrate too=
 much, too early.=C2=A0
When I said that Katerra almost perfectly fit the definition of a vertical =
integrator, this is one of the things I was referring to. The third of five=
 bullets in the definition is =E2=80=9CModularize commoditized components w=
hile controlling overall system integration.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
It seems as if Katerra tried to integrate commoditized components in an att=
empt to drive down their costs and make a margin on producing and selling t=
hem at volume. Which would make sense if the costs of those materials were =
the big bottleneck in home construction, but materials costs aren=E2=80=99t=
 the biggest bottleneck in home construction. High materials costs may incr=
ease the cost of construction, but they don=E2=80=99t typically prevent hom=
es from being built, and savings from cheaper materials can be overwhelmed =
by increases in logistics or labor costs.=C2=A0
So a second lesson: focus on the bottleneck.
Attempting to integrate relatively commoditized components comes with anoth=
er disadvantage. One of the benefits of being a Vertical Integrator is that=
 you can ride advances in certain inputs without locking yourself into any =
but the most critical to your system. Recall that Base Power Company [ http=
s://substack.com/redirect/9c7f9cec-84db-47fd-85b7-e105b3d16092?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =E2=80=9Cassembles=
 and will soon manufacture battery packs itself, but it doesn=E2=80=99t mak=
e battery cells=E2=80=A6 Base believes that cells will be commoditized, and=
 that pack assembly allows it to benefit from that commoditization and pote=
ntially integrate new cell types as better chemistries emerge.=E2=80=9D=C2=
=A0
Katerra, on the other hand, locked itself into certain materials. One that =
Potter calls out specifically is cross-laminated timber, or CLT, a =E2=80=
=9Csuper plywood.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CGreen technologies are enhancing our ability to create more sustai=
nable solutions that also meet structural and aesthetic demands,=E2=80=9D N=
ick Milestone, Katerra's director of mass timber, explained to Dezeen [ htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/2d3c18c3-1d77-4142-9ad3-e62289dd0b6f?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] at the time. =E2=
=80=9CMass timber [ https://substack.com/redirect/051fff29-96a3-454e-829e-6=
54ca304c795?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ], and CLT in particular, is the only material grown for construction t=
hat offers incredible biophilic design solutions.=E2=80=9D
The company spent around $100 million building out a plant to produce CLT, =
acquired high-end mass timber design talent, and could produce =E2=80=9Csom=
ething like 10% of the global supply of CLT, which required selling a LOT o=
f it.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Potter thought that the decision to make CLT manufacturing a part of the bu=
siness model was smart for a number of reasons, including recruiting, separ=
ating Katerra=E2=80=99s products from the traditional view that prefab home=
s were =E2=80=9Ccheap,=E2=80=9D and that with a push towards environmentall=
y friendly materials, the company =E2=80=9Ccould have been a major producer=
 in an expanding market.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Recall, however, that developers on the whole don=E2=80=99t give a flying f=
uck about green technologies or biophilic design solutions if those things =
drive up their costs without sufficiently driving up their revenues. The co=
st of the end product =E2=80=93 the home =E2=80=93 would have to be competi=
tive in order for developers to buy it.=C2=A0
And too often, according to Potter, CLT was not cost-competitive: =E2=80=9C=
CLT is an expensive product, and an easy target for value engineering if pr=
oject costs are too high (we ended up seeing it get cut from a lot of proje=
cts).=E2=80=9D
A specific lesson from Katerra=E2=80=99s CLT experiment might be: don=E2=80=
=99t bet your system on a specific, non-core component.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s easy to say in hindsight. It=E2=80=99s easy to see how you m=
ake that bet in the moment: if you=E2=80=99re right, you are the dominant p=
roducer and customer of an increasingly valuable input to one of the world=
=E2=80=99s largest markets. But the CLT bet was almost like adding Deep Tec=
h risk to Vertical Integration risk, betting that this specific input would=
 be better in the future as opposed to focusing on integrating based on the=
 realities of the present.=C2=A0
It was kind of like adding leverage: amazing if you=E2=80=99re right, destr=
uctive if you=E2=80=99re wrong.=C2=A0
Katerra=E2=80=99s demise wasn=E2=80=99t solely, or maybe even primarily, du=
e to its bet on CLT. Potter cited the slow pace of iteration, bloat from ac=
quisitions, too much bureaucracy, and ultimately, lack of product-market fi=
t, and noted that Katerra=E2=80=99s death was not inevitable: =E2=80=9CIt's=
 easy to imagine that if one or two catastrophic things hadn=E2=80=99t happ=
ened, Katerra could have made it through, and become an amazing story of co=
mpany survival.=E2=80=9D
For his part, Katerra CEO Michael Marks gave a presentation in 2022 [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/7a628762-e13e-4ce7-b2ca-300eaab09398?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] in which he said =
=E2=80=9Cthe articles were all written saying we tried to do too much and t=
he fact is we tried to do too little because we were doing all the hard wor=
k and the money was always going to the developer.=E2=80=9D
Katerra, he argues, wasn=E2=80=99t vertically integrated enough! Just a lit=
tle more vertical integration, and presumably a lot more money to support i=
t, and we may all have been living in Katerra homes one day. This, by the w=
ay, is exactly what Marks is doing with his new business, Onx Homes [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/50086934-568a-4267-93a0-43ec43a4b783?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]: buy land, develop =
it, and vertically integrate the production of precast concrete homes.=C2=
=A0
Which brings up one last lesson: dial in your unit economics before scaling=
 up.
The Lessons of History
That was a lot of history. I appreciate you sticking with me. I think it=E2=
=80=99s crucial to understand what went wrong in the past, why such an obvi=
ous idea as applying better technology and manufacturing processes to a $1 =
trillion market hasn=E2=80=99t produced any massive successes, in order to =
analyze whether Cuby has a shot at breaking the trend.=C2=A0
Just to catch our breath and make sure we=E2=80=99re all on the same page, =
here are the lessons:=C2=A0
Don=E2=80=99t change the house, change how you build it.
Customization is key.
Logistics costs can kill prefab economics.
Gigafactories don=E2=80=99t work for home construction.
Don=E2=80=99t increase costs.
Don=E2=80=99t vertically integrate too much too early.
Focus on the bottleneck.
Don=E2=80=99t bet your system on a specific, non-core component.=C2=A0
Dial in your unit economics before scaling up.=C2=A0
Learning from those lessons, Aleks told me that Cuby is making three bets:=
=C2=A0
Decentralized factories. Gigafactories don=E2=80=99t work. The factories th=
emselves need to be shipped near-site, a hyper-local approach.=C2=A0
Don=E2=80=99t reinvent the home. Preferences from local incumbents, regulat=
ors/inspectors, and end-consumers (renters/owners) are hard to fight. Inste=
ad, change the process and delivery mechanism to be able to build any home =
faster and cheaper.=C2=A0
Don=E2=80=99t build Roadsters. You can=E2=80=99t start out more expensive t=
han existing alternatives. Developers care about cost above all else.=C2=A0
Those bets are the framework =E2=80=93 the Guiding Policy in the parlance o=
f Richard Rumelt=E2=80=99s Good Strategy, Bad Strategy [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/61e6ee43-1141-43a6-899b-7cbef3155d9c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =E2=80=93 on which Cuby has desi=
gned its many interconnected Coherent Actions.
The Cuby Plan
So you want to solve the labor bottleneck in construction and avoid the pit=
falls that have ensnared all of the smart, well-meaning, and well-funded co=
mpanies that came before.=C2=A0
Then you=E2=80=99re going to need to internalize a ton of complexity =E2=80=
=93 just the right amount, at the right level of integration =E2=80=93 and =
make it feel simple to the thousands of individual parties involved in the =
process.=C2=A0
Cuby=E2=80=99s goal is to help others build as many square feet of housing =
as they can with as few hours of skilled labor as possible.=C2=A0
The first question to ask, the answer which is not as obvious as it seems, =
is what product it=E2=80=99s building to achieve that goal. If early prefab=
 companies=E2=80=99 products were homes, and Katerra=E2=80=99s product was =
materials, Cuby=E2=80=99s product is Mobile Micro-Factories=E2=84=A2 (MMFs)=
=2E
=E2=80=9COur product is the factories that move to the construction site, a=
nd using local materials and local labor, begin to produce this kit of part=
s, deliver it onsite, and assemble it onsite. That=E2=80=99s why each facto=
ry can produce roughly a house per day.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
This is how Oleg described MMFs in the intro to Jason Carman=E2=80=99s exce=
llent S3 episode on the company, This Guy is Mass Producing Factories to Bu=
ild Houses.
To really get a tangible sense for what Cuby is building, and how, I highly=
 recommend you take the nine minutes to watch the video, which was shot rem=
otely with Oleg onsite in Belarus and Jason in his earbud from California. =
Oleg explains a lot of the process better than I can.=C2=A0
That doesn=E2=80=99t mean I won=E2=80=99t try.=C2=A0
The most important thing to understand about Cuby is that it produces MMFs,=
 finances them with local partners (often, but not necessarily, developers/=
homebuilders), and ships them to where the houses are going to be built. Th=
ese MMFs produce 37 stages of kits of parts, or PAX, that are then flat-pac=
ked and trucked to the construction site, just-in-time, where unskilled wor=
kers follow detailed, auto-generated instructions to assemble homes in 30 d=
ays, for roughly $100 per square foot.=C2=A0
It, too, wants to do to housing what Ford did to cars, or more precisely wh=
at Toyota did to cars. It just thinks previous attempts didn=E2=80=99t appl=
y the Toyota Production System properly.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CLean manufacturing has worked everywhere else,=E2=80=9D Aleks expl=
ained, =E2=80=9CWhy not in construction?=E2=80=9D
The answer, Cuby believes and we have learned, is the distance between the =
factory and the construction site. Instead of selling parts into the existi=
ng system from a centralized gigafactory, and then watching savings disappe=
ar in logistics and skilled on-site assembly, Cuby controls the whole syste=
m, producing multiple MMFs, putting them near demand, and extending the lea=
n manufacturing process from nearsite to onsite.=C2=A0
Here=E2=80=99s how it works.=C2=A0
Each MMF is essentially a pop-up factory that looks like a tennis bubble en=
veloped by custom shipping containers stuffed with equipment and that can b=
e quickly deployed near construction sites or demand pools. They're designe=
d to service a 150-mile radius, enough volume to keep the factory humming f=
or years, but close enough that logistics costs don=E2=80=99t eat efficienc=
y gains, and that the factory can take feedback from local sites and respon=
d in time. If assembly on-site falls behind by a few steps one day, for exa=
mple, the MMF won=E2=80=99t ship the next day=E2=80=99s components until it=
=E2=80=99s ready.=C2=A0
Essentially, what the MMF does is take in raw materials =E2=80=93 wood, ste=
el, pipes, glass, etc =E2=80=A6 (600 SKUs to be exact) =E2=80=93 and turn t=
hem into kits of parts, or PAX, which are packaged, flat-packed, and trucke=
d to sites in 37 stages, just in time.=C2=A0
Each PAX contains precision-machined components that are compact enough to =
transport efficiently and simple enough to assemble that most of the onsite=
 work can be done by unskilled labor.=C2=A0
The PAX include:
Components made from scratch (like windows, structural framing, helical pie=
r foundations systems, or non-structural insulated sandwich panels, etc.)
Prepared materials (pre-cut drywall, PVC pipes, electrical wires, etc.)
Distributed items (cabinetry, lighting fixtures, toilets, etc.)
Within each MMF, there are dozens of stations, machines, and robots, about =
half of which Cuby buys off the shelf, and half of which it had to design i=
tself (aka proprietary). A few examples, of roughly forty stations, include=
 =E2=80=9CInsulated Glass Unit Manufacturing Station,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CStu=
d Cutting Post,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CPile Welding Post,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CWall=
 Module Assembly Section,=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CDoor Panel With Frame Assem=
bly Section.=E2=80=9D Over three hundred machines and tools operate across =
these forty stations in each MMF.=C2=A0
Roughly 100 workers, most of whom are unskilled, operate each MMF, each ope=
rating specific stations by following lean manufacturing principles. Each s=
tation has a Kanban Board, which flags whether a workflow stage is =E2=80=
=9CTo Do,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CIn Progress,=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9CDone.=E2=80=
=9D Individual tasks are represented as cards that move across the board as=
 they progress, and any employee can raise a flag when they need assistance=
 (this is done physically and as a digital-twin in the software). An additi=
onal 160 work across 20 different on-site home builds (20 homes per month a=
round the MMF, with four unskilled laborers in two shifts on each).
Everything =E2=80=93 in the MMF and onsite =E2=80=93 has its proper place a=
nd label, down to Cuby=E2=80=99s custom-made tool boxes, in which each tool=
 has its own slot, and each box of screw or nails has a card that employees=
 can throw up when they need a refill. It=E2=80=99s meant to keep the whole=
 process running smoothly, even when most of the process is being run by pe=
ople who haven=E2=80=99t worked in factories before thanks to Cuby=E2=80=99=
s MMF Operating System.
What specifically goes into each PAX (and when) is determined by Cuby=E2=80=
=99s software, which takes in architectural drawings =E2=80=93 to figure ou=
t which components are needed for which homes =E2=80=93 and supply chain in=
formation =E2=80=93 sometimes, materials are brought in from China in conta=
iners (cheapest), and sometimes they come from the local Home Depot (most f=
lexible) =E2=80=93 and spits out custom instructions to produce each home=
=E2=80=99s PAX.=C2=A0
Parts are then organized into up to 37 PAX. Each PAX contains everything ne=
eded for a specific phase of the build of a home, packed in the exact order=
 it will be needed on site (e.g., Stage 3, Pax 3 =E2=80=93 installation of =
screwpiles for the foundation). Cuby has built software that fully automate=
s decision making for the order of operations based on push and pull of tas=
ks.
At the beginning of each home project, Cuby dispatches batches of equipment=
 to the construction site, creating what's essentially a mobile extension o=
f the MMF. This includes things like specialized tools, safety equipment, a=
nd even amenities for workers. The goal is to make the on-site assembly pro=
cess as efficient and comfortable as the factory environment.
As construction begins and progresses, PAX are trucked to each job site, tw=
o at a time, just in time (JIT). On site, a team of just four unskilled lab=
orers, working in two shifts, can assemble a home in about 30 days. They're=
 guided by Cuby software, which uses Unreal Engine to auto-generate step-by=
-step 3D instructions for each task. It's like following a very sophisticat=
ed LEGO manual, but for a full-sized house, capable of dynamically changing=
 based on the home that is being built.=C2=A0
These instructions go both ways =E2=80=93 based on their completion, they t=
rigger tasks in the MMF. Everything is push and pull, cause and effect, a m=
ultivariate equation updating in real-time.=C2=A0
This is one of the ways that Cuby is able to reduce the need for skilled la=
bor. By owning the full process, it produces components that are easy to as=
semble, organizes them and ships them to the site in the correct order, and=
 then provides step-by-step instructions. Since up to 70% of the cost of bu=
ilding a home is labor, and since skilled tradespeople are in such short su=
pply, this is critical to Cuby=E2=80=99s ability to deliver homes at all, a=
nd to deliver them for less than traditional construction.=C2=A0
That doesn=E2=80=99t mean that there is no skilled labor, just that Cuby=E2=
=80=99s system is designed to only use skilled labor when it=E2=80=99s real=
ly needed. Tom Chi compares Cuby=E2=80=99s evolution of the construction pr=
ocess to the evolution of the copy machine industry.=C2=A0
Back in the day, if your copy machine had an issue, your company would wait=
, slightly crippled, for the manufacturer to send a copy repairman. Maybe t=
hey=E2=80=99d get there next Thursday, and usually, when they did, they=E2=
=80=99d just remove a paper jam and be on their way. Even something as simp=
le as a paper jam had to be handled by skilled professionals because the ja=
m was somewhere deep in the guts of the system.=C2=A0
Eventually, companies like HP and Epson realized that this was the worst pa=
rt of the user experience, and they redesigned the paper flow to be user se=
rviceable. Now, when there was a jam, the machine would flash the little in=
struction popup and guide users on how to fix it themselves. Sometimes, you=
=E2=80=99d still need to call in the pros for real issues, but most of the =
time, the user could fix the thing and get on with their work.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s how Cuby operates, too, both in the MMFs and onsite. For mos=
t things, Cuby=E2=80=99s process design and software make it easy for unski=
lled labor to complete and troubleshoot tasks. When someone with particular=
 skills is really needed, someone raises a flag, and the pros swoop in.=C2=
=A0
=E2=80=9CAt the end of the day,=E2=80=9D he explained, =E2=80=9Cone electri=
cian can walk through and approve eleven houses, and fix the little things =
that only a trained electrician can fix.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The whole system is designed to build high-quality homes that are responsiv=
e to customer needs, local codes, and supply chains in less time, for less =
money, with less skilled labor:=C2=A0
Speed: A 30-day production cycle is significantly faster than traditional c=
onstruction methods, which can take 6-12 months for a similar home. Even if=
 Cuby is off by 2x or 3x, it=E2=80=99s a massive improvement to the status =
quo.=C2=A0
Cost: Cuby claims they can build at around $100 per square foot based on th=
eir model units, which is competitive with or below what top production hom=
ebuilders can achieve, despite their massive scale advantages.
Quality: By using steel framing and non-structural insulated sandwich panel=
s, Cuby can produce homes that are more durable and energy-efficient than t=
ypical stick-built houses.
Labor Efficiency: This is the bottleneck that everything is designed to sol=
ve.=C2=A0
Customization: Despite the standardized process, Cuby's system allows for h=
undreds of permutations in terms of size, layout, and finishes.
The result is a product that looks and feels like a traditional home - comp=
liant with standard building codes and using familiar materials - but is pr=
oduced in a way that's more akin to advanced manufacturing than traditional=
 construction, with simple process and delivery mechanism improvements.
