=80=93 from labor to materials =E2=80=93 Cuby can integrate it.=C2=A0
The very best Vertical Integrators aren=E2=80=99t threatened by new technol=
ogy, because they=E2=80=99ve built a system designed to plug in the best av=
ailable tools to achieve their goal. By that measure, Cuby has the potentia=
l to be one of the very best Vertical Integrators of this generation.=C2=A0
If the goal really is to build more square feet with less labor, there may =
be no company better positioned than Cuby when the humanoids do arrive, aft=
erall, Cuby=E2=80=99s MMFs are a repeatable environment.=C2=A0
When I asked Oleg about that possibility, he said that was his dream and hi=
s goal:=C2=A0
Right now, everything we do is 100% standardized, we have every task in sof=
tware. We=E2=80=99re like Uber for the worker: get a task, do it, and get p=
aid. And we can take videos of people performing those tasks onsite. In the=
 future, when humanoids are available, we can easily plug them into our sys=
tem.
But halfway through our shared reverie about the future, Oleg pulled us bac=
k to reality.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CThat will be in 5-10 years or so. Now, we=E2=80=99ve opened our fi=
rst factory in China to make MMFs. We will need to open our first two produ=
ction MMFs in the next two years. Then, we need to work up to opening 20 fa=
ctories a year.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CIf you come up with something big and good with no plan to scale,=
=E2=80=9D he warned, =E2=80=9CYou will not earn anything.=E2=80=9D
And that, my friends, is why I think Cuby will win.
Thanks to Claude for editing, and to Aleks, Oleg, Tom, Abdo, Patric, Russel=
l, and the many others who helped me get smart on Cuby and housing construc=
tion, and to Brian Potter for writing such great stuff.
That=E2=80=99s all for today. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Friday=
 with a Weekly Dose.
