ht: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0; position: relative;=
"><strong>A Brief History of Prefab and Manufactured Housing</strong><span>=
&#160;</span></h3><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line=
-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Despite the size of the prize, there is=
 no SpaceX of Home Construction.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55=
); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">In some ways, b=
uilding houses that comply with local zoning and building codes (of which t=
here are approximately 26,000 in the United States alone) in thousands of m=
unicipalities across the country, one at a time, is a harder problem to sol=
ve than building reusable rockets. With rockets, at least, you can put a te=
am of the world&#8217;s best engineers in one place and vertically integrat=
e as much as you need to get the job done. With rockets, you are your own m=
ain customer; the other customers you work with don&#8217;t need to live in=
 your rocket, don&#8217;t need it customized to their personal preferences,=
 don&#8217;t care if it feels like home as long as it gets their payload to=
 orbit.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-=
height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">That hasn&#8217;t stopped a century&#821=
7;s worth of entrepreneurs from trying. To date, while some have had fleeti=
ng or niche success &#8211; Sears Kit Homes, Levittown, or Clayton Homes &#=
8211; not one has really solved the problem. Most have produced more lesson=
s than homes.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px;=
 line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>That&#8217;s good! In </span=
><em>Federalist No. 5, </em><span>John Jay as Publius wrote of the British,=
 </span><strong>&#8220;We may profit from their experience without paying t=
he price which it cost them.&#8221;</strong><span> Cuby may profit from pre=
vious attempts&#8217; experience, without paying the price which it cost th=
em.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Which starts with the insight that st=
rikes every aspiring home construction entrepreneur when they first enter t=
he </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/3db172e1-6b0b-41c5-8ccc-=
69c54ca845b0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Exk=
RNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">Ide=
a Maze</a><span>:</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>We should manufacture=
 houses like we manufacture cars.</strong><span>&#160;</span></p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;"><span>On its website, in bold yellow, housing construction startu=
p </span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/98758878-fc6e-4722-8762-c=
da611175725?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">Diam=
ond Age</a><span> proclaims, &#8220;What Henry Ford did for cars with the a=
ssembly line, Diamond Age does for homes.&#8221;&#160;</span></p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">And it makes sense. Henry Ford figured out that assembly lines de=
crease costs over a century ago, and we&#8217;ve been riding his lessons to=
 material abundance ever since. You and I wouldn&#8217;t be able to afford =
cars if Tesla had to send a team to our driveways to assemble the parts on-=
site. There would be no Moore&#8217;s Law if each chip had to be assembled =
one-at-a-time at the location of the computer it was going to serve.&#160;<=
/p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; =
margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>No, centralized manufacturing is key. The benefi=
ts of manufacturing are manifold: efficiency, speed, cost, consistency, saf=
ety, precision, scalability, and even innovation. Manufacturing something l=
ets you bring it down the </span><strong>learning curve:</strong><span> </s=
pan><strong>as you make more of the thing, you make it more cheaply.</stron=
g></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26p=
x; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">If you want to apply the magic of the assembly line=
 to homebuilding, there are broadly two approaches you can take:&#160;</p><=
ol style=3D"margin-top: 0; padding: 0;"><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"=
><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;"><str=
ong>Prefabricated Homes:</strong><span> Homes are assembled in sections or =
modules in a centralized factory, and then shipped onsite, where they&#8217=
;re assembled on a permanent foundation.</span></p></li><li style=3D"margin=
: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(54, 55, 55)=
; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-=
left: 4px;"><strong>Manufactured Homes: </strong><span>Homes are built enti=
rely in a factory, transported onsite on a steel chassis (which often stays=
 in place), and then plopped onsite.&#160;</span></p></li></ol><p style=3D"=
color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20p=
x 0;">Manufactured homes are their own distinct category &#8211; they are c=
ookie-cutter, often cheap, and they depreciate like cars do. These are not =
typical homes you&#8217;re thinking of when you think about a home &#8211; =
they&#8217;re built differently, face different regulations, and generally =
have a lower perceived value. There are some large manufactured homes compa=
nies, like Clayton Homes, which Berkshire Hathaway acquired for $1.7 billio=
n in 2003, but they serve a specific niche, the low-end of the market.&#160=
