0 20px 0;">Because it costs what it costs to transport a shipping container=
 over the same distance, as long as you&#8217;re within weight limits, ship=
ping a 40-foot container full of tightly-packed 2x4s is more cost-effective=
 than shipping a container with fully constructed wall panels or even rooms=
, which contain a lot of empty volume.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, =
55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Thi=
s is one of the reasons that so much of construction is just sending finish=
ed inputs (windows, doors, cabinetry, fixtures, flooring, and appliances) a=
nd non-finished inputs (like lumber, concrete, drywall, insulation, and roo=
fing materials) to the site for local crews to take care of.&#160; Even sti=
ll, the current process requires skilled labor to do messy, non-structured =
work to them even before install, resulting in mistakes, lots of rework, an=
d waste. Building an average 2,000 square foot home generates </span><stron=
g><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/91003d89-3c70-4f60-8076-d90040a5=
c080?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" re=
l style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">four tons o=
f waste</a></strong><span>!</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Pre-fab 1.0 w=
as stuck somewhere in between: higher logistics costs, a little less waste,=
 a lot of on-site work and assembly. Paying so much on logistics and </span=
><em>then</em><span> paying skilled people to handle so much on-site makes =
the economics hard to pencil.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55);=
 font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">More than anythin=
g else, this is what killed Prefab 1.0.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54,=
 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Prefab 1=
=2E0 was almost a product in search of=20=
a problem. It was driven by new techno=
logy &#8211; Computer-Aided Design (CAD), Building Information Modeling (BI=
M), and Computer Numerical Control (CNC) Machines &#8211; and the belief th=
at maybe, now, with these new technological tools, we might finally be able=
 to realize the dream of doing to homes what Ford did to cars.&#160;</p><p =
style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;">Cars, however, are different than homes. For one important t=
hing, they are mobile: once assembled, you can drive them off the line. Mor=
e efficiently, you can put a bunch of them on the back of one truck and car=
ry them to the lot that will sell them to the customers who will drive them=
 home. You don&#8217;t need to cut down trees or hire helicopters to get ca=
rs from the place they&#8217;re made to the place they&#8217;ll be used, no=
r do you have to do final assembly in the driveway, calling in teams of ski=
lled professionals to snap their pieces into place, hook them up to plumbin=
g, or connect their wires.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); fon=
t-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>So here&#8217;s=
 a fourth lesson: </span><strong>centralized gigafactories don&#8217;t work=
 for home construction</strong><span>.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54,=
 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Expensiv=
e, centralized factories have a number of disadvantages: they require more =
capital and time to launch, before the process is perfected, feedback from =
the site takes longer, they can&#8217;t produce with specific local codes i=
n mind, and you need to keep running the factory even when demand slows due=
 to high fixed costs.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-siz=
e: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Above all else, if you bui=
ld something for less in the factory, and pay more than you&#8217;ve saved =
to transport and assemble it, you increase costs. And increased costs don&#=
8217;t work.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">If there&#8217;s one thing develope=
rs will not countenance, it&#8217;s adding cost. They like making money, an=
d more contractually, they&#8217;re obligated to pay back the debt they tak=
e on to get each project going. The formula that drives them is:&#160;</p><=
p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; marg=
in: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>Return on Investment =3D (Sale Price - Costs) / Co=
sts&#160;</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>There are others, of course. =
They care about IRR and ROC and Profit Margin and Absorption Rate and Debt =
Service Coverage Ratio and Construction Cost per Square Foot and Sales Pric=
e per Square Foot and Inventory Turnover, </span><strong>not a single one o=
f which improves with higher costs</strong><span>.&#160;</span></p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;"><span>So this is a fifth, and maybe most important, lesson: </spa=
n><strong>don&#8217;t increase costs.</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54=
, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>W=
hich brings us to </span><strong>Katerra</strong><span>.&#160;</span></p><p=
 style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margi=
n: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Katerra is worth studying on its own because it was t=
he most well-funded, ambitious, and modern attempt to build a Vertical Inte=
grator in housing construction. It fit the Vertical Integrator definition <=
/span><em>almost </em><span>to a T. But that </span><em>almost</em><span> w=
as the difference between a $100 billion outcome and $2 billion of (mostly)=
 SoftBank&#8217;s money down the drain.&#160;</span></p><h3 class=3D"header=
