gb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Ba=
ck in the day, if your copy machine had an issue, your company would wait, =
slightly crippled, for the manufacturer to send a copy repairman. Maybe the=
y&#8217;d get there next Thursday, and usually, when they did, they&#8217;d=
 just remove a paper jam and be on their way. Even something as simple as a=
 paper jam had to be handled by skilled professionals because the jam was s=
omewhere deep in the guts of the system.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54=
, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Eventua=
lly, companies like HP and Epson realized that this was the worst part of t=
he user experience, and they redesigned the paper flow to be user serviceab=
le. Now, when there was a jam, the machine would flash the little instructi=
on popup and guide users on how to fix it themselves. Sometimes, you&#8217;=
d still need to call in the pros for real issues, but most of the time, the=
 user could fix the thing and get on with their work.&#160;</p><p style=3D"=
color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20p=
x 0;">That&#8217;s how Cuby operates, too, both in the MMFs and onsite. For=
 most things, Cuby&#8217;s process design and software make it easy for uns=
killed labor to complete and troubleshoot tasks. When someone with particul=
ar skills is really needed, someone raises a flag, and the pros swoop in.&#=
160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 2=
6px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">&#8220;At the end of the day,&#8221; he explained=
, &#8220;one electrician can walk through and approve eleven houses, and fi=
x the little things that only a trained electrician can fix.&#8221;&#160;</=
p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; m=
argin: 0 0 20px 0;">The whole system is designed to build high-quality home=
s that are responsive to customer needs, local codes, and supply chains in =
less time, for less money, with less skilled labor:&#160;</p><ol style=3D"m=
argin-top: 0; padding: 0;"><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"=
box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-heigh=
t: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;"><strong>Speed:</s=
trong><span> A 30-day production cycle is significantly faster than traditi=
onal construction methods, which can take 6-12 months for a similar home. E=
ven if Cuby is off by 2x or 3x, it&#8217;s a massive improvement to the sta=
tus quo.&#160;</span></p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=
=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;"><strong>Cost:=
</strong><span> Cuby claims they can build at around $100 per square foot b=
ased on their model units, which is competitive with or below what top prod=
uction homebuilders can achieve, despite their massive scale advantages.</s=
pan></p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: bo=
