rcialization Efforts Underway</em></figcaption></figure></div><p style=3D"c=
olor: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px=
 0;">We&#8217;ve covered a ton, and we haven&#8217;t even covered it all. O=
ne tidbit that we didn&#8217;t cover but that I have to mention is that Ole=
g does this thing where he sees a material, component, or even full robot a=
nd finds the same thing &#8211; maybe 80-90% as good, but good enough, for =
like 10-20% of the cost in China. Because he&#8217;s not American, and beca=
use he&#8217;s spent so much time there, he gets the non-American pricing.&=
#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: =
26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">But I digress. If I kept adding stories like tha=
t, we&#8217;d never get to Phase II, and it&#8217;s fun to imagine the futu=
re in which Cuby pulls this off.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55=
); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>While Pha=
se I benefits greatly from the right level of vertical integration, </span>=
<strong>Phase II</strong><span> is where the real power of becoming a Verti=
cal Integrator at scale kicks in.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54=
, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">First, =
there are just the benefits to time and scale that accrue to a continually =
improving organization. Cuby&#8217;s goal is to increase output of square f=
ootage over skilled labor hours required to assemble a home by 20% every ye=
ar, and bring costs down in the process. While it will start out at parity =
or lower cost than traditional homebuilders, the benefit of manufacturing i=
s that costs can come down the learning curve. At some point, if everything=
 works, it will be very hard for anyone to match Cuby&#8217;s cost per squa=
re foot, and it will be very hard for developers that don&#8217;t partner w=
ith Cuby.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; lin=
e-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>One of the most interesting oppo=
rtunities for Cuby in Phase II is to </span><strong>pull a reverse-Katerra<=
/strong><span>: get to scale, figure out which materials and pieces of the =
supply chain it uses most often, and then vertically integrate those. It ca=
n supply its own growing fleet of MMFs with essential materials, capturing =
more margin while lowering costs, and potentially even supply other builder=
s.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; lin=
e-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">This will be a balance &#8211; for som=
e things, it makes sense to vertically integrate; for others, it makes sens=
e to let the market do its thing and bring down costs that Cuby can benefit=
 from. Aleks mentioned, as an example, that if companies develop cost-compe=
titive low-carbon concrete or steel, Cuby at scale could become one of the =
product&#8217;s biggest purchasers. There are many such cases.&#160;</p><p =
style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>It may also </span><strong>vertically integrate into l=
and acquisition and development</strong><span>, backed by debt or project f=
inancing with a lower cost of capital than venture dollars. Aleks is very c=
lear, perhaps informed by his time at WeWork, that venture capital should b=
e used for R&amp;D and not for scale.&#160;</span></p><div class=3D"caption=
