%;"><em>FRED</em></figcaption></figure></div><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55,=
 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Technologica=
lly, it&#8217;s a great time to automate home construction, if you do it ri=
ght. As mentioned, Cuby auto-generates instructions for its workers using U=
nreal Engine. That&#8217;s insane. That wasn&#8217;t possible even two or t=
hree years ago. While humanoids aren&#8217;t ready quite yet, robotics alre=
ady allows Cuby to automate things in the factory that the Prefab 1.0 conti=
ngent could have only dreamed of twenty years ago. It&#8217;s not hard to s=
quint and imagine self-driving trucks bringing materials into MMFs and driv=
ing finished components back out to construction sites.&#160;</p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;"><span>With so much innovation about to hit construction, one ques=
tion you might ask is: </span><strong>why Cuby?</strong><span>&#160;</span>=
</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;=
 margin: 0 0 20px 0;">In other words, why now? Why not the next company tha=
t builds with an even more advanced technological toolkit at its disposal?&=
#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: =
26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Take </span><a href=3D"https://substack.co=
m/redirect/195a8260-bfb3-47f8-aca7-1a3c612d1380?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55=
); text-decoration: underline;">Monumental</a><span>, founded by former CER=
N physicist Salar al Khafaji, one of my favorite companies in the space. Mo=
numental builds robots that build homes, starting with bricklaying. It acts=
 as a subcontractor, hired by general contractors to deliver a specific job=
, which it happens to do with its own robots. Its robots are currently depl=
oyed in the field, earning money and solving part of the labor shortage. Sa=
lar is a genius and an excellent founder who cares deeply about reigniting =
progress and returning beauty to architecture. The company&#8217;s strategy=
 is brilliant, and its ambitions are massive.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"c=
olor: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px=
 0;">Is Monumental a threat to Cuby?&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55=
, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Quite the o=
pposite. I think that Monumental&#8217;s success makes Cuby&#8217;s more li=
kely, and Cuby&#8217;s makes Monumental&#8217;s more likely. As Monumental&=
#8217;s robots do more and more work that subcontractors do today, Cuby can=
 work with them to build more (beautiful) square feet with less skilled lab=
or. And as Cuby grows, it gives Monumental more opportunity to work within =
a system designed for automated precision. Both can win.&#160;</p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">This same logic applies with other construction tech companies. I=
f they deliver something better, cheaper, and faster than it&#8217;s done t=
oday &#8211; from labor to materials &#8211; Cuby can integrate it.&#160;</=
p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; m=
argin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The very best Vertical Integrators aren&#8217;t t=
hreatened by new technology, because they&#8217;ve built a system designed =
to plug in the best available tools to achieve their goal. By that measure,=
 </span><strong>Cuby has the potential to be one of the very best Vertical =
Integrators of this generation.&#160;</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54=
, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">If the =
goal really is to build more square feet with less labor, there may be no c=
ompany better positioned than Cuby when the humanoids do arrive, afterall, =
Cuby&#8217;s MMFs are a repeatable environment.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color:=
 rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">=
When I asked Oleg about that possibility, he said that was his dream and hi=
s goal:&#160;</p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #0c2427; margi=
n: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px=
; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em><span>Righ=
t now, everything we do is 100% standardized, we have every task in softwar=
e. We&#8217;re like Uber for the worker: get a task, do it, and get paid. A=
nd we can take videos of people performing those tasks onsite. </span><stro=
ng>In the future, when humanoids are available, we can easily plug them int=
o our system.</strong></em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, =
55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">But halfway t=
hrough our shared reverie about the future, Oleg pulled us back to reality.=
&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height:=
 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">&#8220;That will be in 5-10 years or so. Now, w=
e&#8217;ve opened our first factory in China to make MMFs. We will need to =
open our first two production MMFs in the next two years. Then, we need to =
work up to opening 20 factories a year.&#8221;&#160;</p><div class=3D"capti=
